value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: D-myo-inositol 1,3,4-trisphosphate + H2O = myo-inositol 1,3-bisphosphate + phosphate.
Binding to an aryl hydrocarbon receptor.
Binding to vinculin, a protein found in muscle, fibroblasts, and epithelial cells that binds actin and appears to mediate attachment of actin filaments to integral proteins of the plasma membrane.
Catalysis of the reaction: 5-oxo-L-proline + ATP + 2 H2O = L-glutamate + ADP + 2 H+ + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: CDP + alcohol = CMP + phosphatidyl alcohol.

Catalysis of the hydrolysis of a substrate by a catalytic mechanism that involves a catalytic triad consisting of a serine nucleophile that is activated by a proton relay involving an acidic residue (e.g. aspartate or glutamate) and a basic residue (usually histidine).
Catalysis of the reaction: L-cysteine + O2 = 3-sulfino-L-alanine + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + glycine = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + sarcosine.
Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine + phosphatidylinositol = UDP + N-acetyl-D-glucosaminylphosphatidylinositol.
A heterodimeric complex that catalyzes the trimming of glucose residues from N-linked core glycans on newly synthesized glycoproteins.

definition.value: Note that alpha-glucosidase I functions as a monomer, and therefore does not have a corresponding cellular component term.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + diphthine + NH4 = ADP + diphthamide + H+ + phosphate.

The modification of peptidyl-histidine to 2'-(3-carboxamido-3-(trimethylammonio)propyl)-L-histidine, known as diphthamide, found in translation elongation factor EF-2. The process occurs in eukaryotes and archaea but not eubacteria.
The hydroxylation of peptidyl-lysine to form peptidyl-hydroxylysine.

label.value: peptidyl-pyroglutamic acid biosynthetic process, using glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of peptidyl-pyroglutamic acid, catalyzed by glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase activity ; GO:0016603'.

value.value: The gamma-carboxylation of peptidyl-glutamic acid; catalyzed by the vitamin K dependent gamma-glutamyl carboxylase.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'gamma-glutamyl carboxylase activity ; GO:0008488'.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: L-aspartate + acetyl-CoA = N-acetyl-L-aspartate + CoA + H+.
The acetylation of the N-terminal aspartic acid of proteins; catalyzed by aspartate N-acetyltransferase.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'aspartate N-acetyltransferase activity ; GO:0017188'.

value.value: The acetylation of a glutamine residue in protein to form the N5-methyl-L-glutamine derivative. The occurrence of this modification has not been confirmed. Its annotation in sequence databases is either due to the misidentification of 2-pyrrolidone-5-carboxylic acid, or to inappropriate homolog comparisons when proteolytic modification is more probable.
The acetylation of the N-terminal methionine of proteins to form the derivative N-acetyl-L-methionine.
The acetylation of the N-terminal glutamic acid of proteins to form the derivate acetyl-glutamic acid.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'aspartate N-acetyltransferase activity ; GO:0017188'.

value.value: The acetylation of the peptidyl-lysine of proteins to form the derivative peptidyl-N6-acetyl-L-lysine.

definition.value: See also the molecular function term 'tubulin N-acetyltransferase activity ; GO:0019799'.

value.value: The formylation of the N-terminal amino acid of proteins.
The glucuronylation of the N-terminal amino acid of proteins.
The glucuronylation of the N-terminal glycine of proteins to form the derivative D-glucuronyl-N-glycine.
The myristoylation of the N-terminal glycine of proteins to form the derivative N-myristoyl-glycine.
The covalent attachment of a palmitoyl group to a nitrogen (N) atom in an N-terminal cysteine residue to form N-palmitoyl-L-cysteine.
The methylation of the N-terminal alanine of proteins.
The trimethylation of the N-terminal alanine of proteins to form the derivative peptidyl-N,N,N-trimethyl-L-alanine.
The methylation of the N-terminal glycine of proteins to form the derivative N-methylglycine.
The methylation of the N-terminal proline of proteins to form the derivative N,N-dimethyl-L-proline.

The methylation of peptidyl-L-histidine to form peptidyl-L-1'-methyl-L-histidine (otherwise known as tau-methylhistidine, tele-methylhistidine) or peptidyl-L-3'-methyl-L-histidine (otherwise known as pi-methylhistidine, pros-methylhistidine).
The methylation of peptidyl-lysine to form either the mono-, di- or trimethylated derivative.
The methylation of peptidyl-lysine to form peptidyl-N6,N6,N6-trimethyl-L-lysine.
Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + calmodulin L-lysine = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + calmodulin N6-methyl-L-lysine.
The methylation of peptidyl-lysine to form peptidyl-N6-methyl-L-lysine.
The methylation of peptidyl-lysine to form peptidyl-N6,N6-dimethyl-L-lysine.
Catalysis of the transfer of a myristoyl group to the N6 nitrogen atom on a lysine residue of a peptide or protein molecule.
Catalysis of the transfer of a palmitoyl group to the N6 nitrogen atom on a lysine residue of a peptide or protein molecule.

The oxidation of the terminal amino-methylene groups of peptidyl-L-lysine or peptidyl-5-hydroxy-L-lysine to aldehyde groups to form allysine or hydroxyallysine residues, respectively; these are intermediates in the formation of covalent cross-links between adjacent polypeptide chains in proteins such as collagens.

label.value: N-terminal protein amino acid deamination, from amino carbon

value.value: The oxidative deamination of the alpha carbon of an encoded N-terminal amino acid, to form pyruvic acid retaining an amide bond between its 1-carboxyl group and the adjacent residue. The pyruvate 2-oxo group may become an enzyme active site, or it may be reduced to an alcohol.

label.value: peptidyl-L-3-phenyllactic acid biosynthetic process from peptidyl-phenylalanine

value.value: The modification of a N-terminal peptidyl-phenylalanine residue by either oxidative deamination or by transamination and subsequent reduction to form peptidyl-L-3-phenyllactic acid.
The linkage of cytochromes and other heme proteins to heme.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-histidyl-[protein] + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = N(tele)-methyl-L-histidyl-[protein] + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.
The phosphopantetheinylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O-phosphopantetheine-L-serine.
The acetylation of the N-terminal lysine of proteins.

label.value: peptidyl-L-3-oxoalanine biosynthetic process from peptidyl-cysteine or peptidyl-serine

value.value: The modification of peptidyl-cysteine or peptidyl-serine to peptidyl-L-3-oxoalanine; characteristic of the active sites of arylsulfatases.
The process of conversion of a L-amino acid into its enantiomer, the corresponding D-amino acid.
The addition of glycyl units covalently bound to the gamma carboxyl group peptidyl-glutamic acid.
The addition of one or more alpha-linked glutamyl units to the gamma carboxyl group of peptidyl-glutamic acid.
A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a C atom.
